1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,544
In the previous lesson, we described the
marketing mix and applied the seven Ps

2
00:00:04,544 --> 00:00:06,641
services model to an advisory offer.

3
00:00:07,641 --> 00:00:12,656
In this lesson, we'll identify the four
characteristics of services and explain

4
00:00:12,656 --> 00:00:14,328
how each shapes marketing.

5
00:00:15,328 --> 00:00:19,508
Services behave differently from products
in four important ways.

6
00:00:19,508 --> 00:00:24,166
These are often summarised as
intangibility, inseparability,

7
00:00:24,166 --> 00:00:26,613
variability, and perishability.

8
00:00:27,613 --> 00:00:31,978
Intangibility means a service cannot be
seen or touched before it is bought.

9
00:00:32,978 --> 00:00:36,879
Inseparability means it is produced and
consumed at the same time.

10
00:00:37,879 --> 00:00:42,291
Variability means its quality can change
from one engagement to the next.

11
00:00:43,291 --> 00:00:48,691
Perishability means unused capacity, such
as an idle consultant's time, cannot be

12
00:00:48,691 --> 00:00:49,839
stored for later.

13
00:00:50,839 --> 00:00:53,672
Each characteristic creates a distinct
challenge.

14
00:00:54,672 --> 00:00:59,681
Because services are intangible, clients
struggle to judge quality in advance, so

15
00:00:59,681 --> 00:01:01,684
the firm must offer reassurance.

16
00:01:01,684 --> 00:01:05,805
Because they are inseparable, the
client's experience of the team becomes

17
00:01:05,805 --> 00:01:07,350
part of the product itself.

18
00:01:07,350 --> 00:01:12,133
Variability raises the risk of
inconsistent delivery, which can damage a

19
00:01:12,133 --> 00:01:13,480
hard-won reputation.

20
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:19,479
Perishability means a firm must keep its
people productive, since time that goes

21
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:20,935
unsold is lost revenue.

22
00:01:21,935 --> 00:01:24,582
Firms manage these challenges
deliberately.

23
00:01:24,582 --> 00:01:29,366
To counter intangibility, they make the
work tangible through credentials, case

24
00:01:29,366 --> 00:01:31,084
studies, and a strong brand.

25
00:01:32,084 --> 00:01:36,986
To manage variability, they standardise
their methods and invest in training, so

26
00:01:36,986 --> 00:01:39,096
quality holds steady across teams.

27
00:01:40,096 --> 00:01:45,864
These responses turn the characteristics
of services from a weakness into a source

28
00:01:45,864 --> 00:01:46,505
of trust.

29
00:01:47,505 --> 00:01:50,570
FinSage feels perishability most keenly.

30
00:01:50,570 --> 00:01:55,744
When its pipeline is thin, experienced
advisors sit idle, and that time can

31
00:01:55,744 --> 00:01:57,072
never be recovered.

32
00:01:57,072 --> 00:02:01,548
A clearer view of its market, which we'll
build later in the course, would help

33
00:02:01,548 --> 00:02:04,131
FinSage keep its people consistently
deployed.

34
00:02:04,131 --> 00:02:06,035
Let's stop the lesson here.

35
00:02:07,035 --> 00:02:11,447
In this lesson, we first identified the
four characteristics of services.

36
00:02:12,447 --> 00:02:15,466
We then examined the challenge each one
creates.

37
00:02:16,466 --> 00:02:19,670
Finally, we saw how firms respond to
them.

38
00:02:20,670 --> 00:02:24,853
In the next lesson, we'll turn to the
core principles of marketing for advisory

39
00:02:24,853 --> 00:02:25,175
firms.

